#### 1. ToString() Multi-Allocation Storm (7+ allocations per call) 🔴 Critical
**Impact:** Each `ToString()` call on a hot path allocates 3-7 intermediate strings via `Contains`, `Replace`, and format operations — devastating at thousands of calls/sec.  
**Files:** DataSize.cs:L168-225  
**Fix:** Replace the branching `Contains`/`Replace` approach with a simple switch on `LargestWholeNumberSymbol` and direct `double.ToString()` + string concatenation with the unit suffix. Use `string.Create` or `Span<char>`/`stackalloc` for zero-alloc formatting:

```csharp
public override string ToString() => ToString("0.##", CultureInfo.CurrentCulture);

public string ToString(string? format, IFormatProvider? formatProvider = null)
{
    format ??= "0.##";
    formatProvider ??= CultureInfo.CurrentCulture;

    var (value, symbol) = GetLargestWholeNumber();
    return $"{value.ToString(format, formatProvider)} {symbol}";
}

private (double Value, string Symbol) GetLargestWholeNumber()
{
    if (Math.Abs(Terabytes) >= 1) return (Terabytes, TerabyteSymbol);
    if (Math.Abs(Gigabytes) >= 1) return (Gigabytes, GigabyteSymbol);
    if (Math.Abs(Megabytes) >= 1) return (Megabytes, MegabyteSymbol);
    if (Math.Abs(Kilobytes) >= 1) return (Kilobytes, KilobyteSymbol);
    if (Math.Abs(Bytes) >= 1) return (Bytes, ByteSymbol);
    return (Bits, BitSymbol);
}
